SALMONELLOSIS, SHEEP - NEW ZEALAND (MID CANTERBURY)
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
Date: Tue, 01 Sep 1998 12:03:29 +1200
Source: News media, edited. - Mod.MHJ
Via: Naomi Boxall <Naomi.Boxall.1@uni.massey.ac.nz>

Farmers warned to take care with _Salmonella_
[South Island] Aug 28 - The epidemic of _Salmonella_-related abortions in
sheep throughout Otago and Southland has grown to worrying proportions.
Pockets of farms in Otago and Southland have been affected by _Salmonella
brandenburg_ which causes sheep to develop a fever, abort lambs, and
possibly die. Some farmers have also been affected by the disease,
suffering from abdominal cramps, vomiting, diarrhoea and fever.
The strain broke out in Canterbury last season, and has spread further
south, Invermay Animal Health Laboratory vet Marjorie Orr told NZPA today.
"It was at a very low level up until last year, and then there was a big
outbreak in Canterbury. This year it suddenly appeared down here, and it's
just taken off like wildfire." She said clusters of adjacent farms were
affected. "It won't spread if people take really good care to wash hands
and vehicles so it doesn't spread from farm to farm. If they treat it
early, it will be contained." It was uncertain how the disease spread, but
Ms Orr said it was likely "anything that carries mud and faeces, like boots
and vehicles and seagulls' feet, will take it from paddock to paddock."
Sheep could also carry the bacteria without showing symptoms. "That may be
how it arrived here (in Otago) -- it may have been brought in by sheep from
some other area, like Canterbury." Gore vet Ewen Miller said farmers were
advised to remove aborted lambs as soon as possible, isolate the ewes, and
take care of personal hygiene. It appeared to be a seasonal problem, as
sheep were affected close to lambing.
The disease was recorded a few years ago but in very low levels. A
broad-spectrum antibiotic could be used if the disease was spotted early,
but a salmonella vaccine would not be effective. Antibiotics were needed
very early, "but really it's too late to save the lambs," Ms Orr said. "You
can't prevent it but you can treat it if you catch it very early."
