Date: Tue, 01 Sep 1998 12:06:53 +1200
From: Naomi Boxall <Naomi.Boxall.1@uni.massey.ac.nz>

Fears sheep _Salmonella_ outbreak spreading
[South Island] Aug 31 - Farmers fear the sheep-killer disease caused by
_Salmonella brandenburg_ is spreading north through the South Island after
a fresh case was reported in Darfield, Canterbury.
Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry spokeswoman Debbie Gee said today 21
mobs of sheep from 19 Mid Canterbury farms had been tested. Twelve were
confirmed as having the disease. Nine more were awaiting confirmation, but
indications were "highly likely" that they would also test positive. Ms Gee
said eight cases had been confirmed in Ashburton, three in Rakaia and one
in Darfield.
Ashburton Veterinary Centre marketing manager Chris McCarthy said up to
1,200 sheep had died in Mid Canterbury. Methven farmer Hugh Weir said 100
of his ewes had aborted and 20 had subsequently died. He felt for the
affected sheep, which were obviously suffering. "I wouldn't like to be as
crook as some of the sheep," he said. Mr Weir said he first noticed the
disease four weeks ago. Most of his dead ewes were scanned and had been
carrying twins. "When we took samples to the vet they said it could be
salmonella but no one seemed to be getting too panicked at that stage," he
said. He vaccinated his 3,000 ewes last week.
South Canterbury medical officer Dr John Holmes said eight cases of the
disease had been reported in humans in South Canterbury this year but he
was unsure if they had contracted the disease from stock. Five farmers in
Southland and Otago had been diagnosed with the disease.
Meanwhile, seagulls in Mid Canterbury were being shot and collected for
examination. Mr McCarthy said the dead birds would be sent to the animal
health laboratory in Lincoln, near Christchurch, for examination. Ms Gee
said scientists "strongly suspected" seagulls were spreading the disease on
their feet or beaks. Tests were being made to discover whether seagulls
played a part in spreading the disease and if they were carriers.
Ashburton vet Jonathan Grant urged all farmers to maintain strict hygiene
when dealing with stock and to ensure the chances of further spread were
minimised. "Farmers should control dogs so they don't wander on to other
properties and bring the disease on to their own property," he said.
Farmers should [clean and] disinfect their boots and wash clothing after
dealing with stock. If they thought their stock had the disease they should
contact their vet. Farmers had been encouraged to vaccinate stock or
administer antibiotics to help fight _Salmonella brandenburg_. Mr Grant
said there had been some debate about the effectiveness of vaccinations but
he believed two shots were effective. Each vaccination cost 40 cents..
